  "text": "Mice receiving control CD19 CAR T cells developed rapid disease progression and were euthanized by day 30 (Figure 6A-B) . In contrast, mice receiving CD5 CAR T cells were significantly protected from rapid progression and their median survival was prolonged by .150% (28 days in control CAR group vs 71 days in CD5 CAR group; P 5 .0003) ( Figure 6A-B) . We also observed superior tumor control by T cells transduced with a CD5 CAR harboring only the CH 3 portion of the IgG1 spacer compared with T cells expressing a full-spacer CAR (supplemental Figure 11 ), consistent with prior reports. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] We next evaluated the capacity of CD5 CAR T cells to control an established tumor by injecting CAR T cells later, on day 6 and 9 postimplantation. By day 6, the overall tumor burden in control and CD5 CAR groups was similar. In the group receiving the CD5 CAR T-cell injection, however, the disease was significantly reduced by day 12 (Figure 6C-D) . Median survival of the mice was significantly extended from 42 days with control CAR to 114 days with CD5 CAR (P 5 .0018) ( Figure 6E ). No benefit was seen from CD19 CAR T cells despite their higher frequency in peripheral blood after infusion (supplemental Figure 12A,C) . The For personal use only. on January 1, 2018. by guest www.bloodjournal.org From lower CD4:CD8 ratio in CD5 CAR T cells (supplemental Figure 12B ,D) likely resulted from better expansion of effector/memory CD8 1 T cells or increased susceptibility of CD4 1 T cells to fratricide by CD5 CAR T cells.",
